Japan, China, India, Thailand, South Korea: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview

-- B y   K h a l i d   Q a y u m
-- 
2011-08-10T22:56:56Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-10/japan-china-india-thailand-south-korea-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will hold media
briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m.  The government will release data on machine orders for June
at 8:50 a.m. in  Tokyo . Factory orders rose 1.7 percent, from an
increase of 3 percent in the previous month, according to the
median forecast in a Bloomberg survey.  The Ministry of Finance will sell 2.4 trillion yen ($31
billion) of five-year notes. Results are due at 12:45 p.m.  The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond due June 2021
was little changed at 1.035 percent, according to Japan Bond
Trading Co., the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker. The
yen traded at 76.70 per dollar at 7:50 a.m. in Tokyo.  China :  Agricultural Development Bank of China plans to
sell 15 billion yuan ($2.3 billion) of one-year bonds.  China
Development Bank  will sell a combined 30 billion yuan of 153-day
and 10-year securities.  The yield on the 3.99 percent bond due June 2021 was at
3.97 percent. The yuan was at 6.4181 per dollar.  India : The commerce ministry will publish food inflation
data for the week ended July 30. The index rose 8.04 percent in
the previous week from a year earlier.  The yield on the 7.8 percent bond due April 2021 was 8.20
percent. The rupee was at 45.2200 per dollar.  Malaysia: The government will sell 80 million ringgit ($27
million) of 91-day bills and 100 million ringgit of 273-day
Islamic notes.  The yield on the 4.16 percent bond due July 2021 was 3.69
percent. The ringgit was at 3.0055 per dollar.  South Korea : The Bank of  Korea  will leave the seven-day
repurchase rate at 3.25 percent, according to 10 of 15
economists in a Bloomberg survey before the decision today. Five
forecast a 25-basis point increase.  The yield on the 3.5 percent government bonds due June 2014
was at 3.46 percent. The won was at 1,080.20 per dollar.  Thailand: The University of the Thai Chamber of Commerce
will release an index of  consumer confidence  for July at 10:30
a.m. in Bangkok. The gauge was at 72.3 in June, the highest
since January. The central bank will release data on foreign-
exchange reserves for the week ended Aug. 5. Reserves gained 1
percent to $187.6 billion the previous week.  The yield on the 5.4 percent debt due July 2016 was 3.49
percent. The baht was at 29.89 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Khalid Qayum in Singapore at 
 kqayum@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
